graphic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Stockhay","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English:","habitational name from Stockham in Witheridge (Devon), from Old English <i>stōd</i> ‘stud, herd of horses’ + <i>cumb</i> ‘valley’.","habitational name from Stockham Marsh in Bremhill (Wiltshire), which may derive from Old English <i>stocc</i> ‘tree trunk, stump’ + <i>hamm</i> ‘water meadow’ or <i>hām</i> ‘village, homestead’."],"variants":[{"name":"Stocum","meanings":["English: variant of   Stockham  ."]}]},{"name":"Joan","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Contracted form of Old French <i>Jo(h)anne</i>, from Latin <i>Io(h)anna</i> (  see  Joanna  ). In England this was the usual feminine form of   John   from the Middle English period onwards and was extremely popular, but in the 16th and 17th centuries it steadily lost ground to   Jane .  It was strongly revived in the first part of the 20th century, partly under the influence of  George Bernard Shaw's  play St Joan (  1923 ), based on the life of  Joan of Arc  (  1412–31 ). Claiming to be guided by the voices of the saints, she persuaded the French dauphin to defy the occupying English forces and have himself crowned, and she led the French army that raised the siege of Orleans in  1429 . The following year she was captured by the Burgundians and sold to the English, and a year later she was burned at the stake for witchcraft at the age of 18 or 19. Her story has captured the imagination of many writers, and she is variously portrayed as a national and political hero, a model of apolitical straightforwardness and honesty, and a religious heroine. She was canonized in  1920 . More recent influences have included the American film actress  Joan Crawford  (  1908–77 , born  Lucille le Sueur ), the British actress  Joan Collins  (  b. 1933 ), the American comedienne  Joan Rivers  (  b. 1933 ), and the West Indian pop singer  Joan Armatrading  (  b. 1950 )."],"variants":[{"name":"John","meanings":["Greek: the Lord gave graciously; whom Jehovah gave; whom Jehovah bestowed."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Joan de Stockhay was born in 1230, in Brockham, Devon, England, United Kingdom, her father, John de Stockhay, was 25 and her mother, Mrs. John Stockhay, was 20. She had at least 1 daughter with William Le Waleys. She died in England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"1230?–":"1230–Surnud","1230–Female":"1230–Surnud","1225–1276":"1225–1276","1225–1270":"1225–1270","1260–1320":"1260–1320","1250–Male":"1250–Surnud","1205–Male":"1205–Surnud","1210–Female":"1210–Surnud","1205":"1205","1225":"1225","1210":"1210","1320":"1320","1276":"1276","1230?":"1230","1230":"1230","1250":"1250","1260":"1260","1270":"1270","Abt 1229":"umbes 1229","Stockham, Devon, England":"Brockham, Devon, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Somerset, England":"Somerset, England","Raleigh, Devon, England":"Farleigh, Devon, Inglismaa, United Kingdom",",Devon,England":"Devon, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","England":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1230?–":"1230–Kuollut","1230–Female":"1230–Kuollut","1225–1276":"1225–1276","1225–1270":"1225–1270","1260–1320":"1260–1320","1250–Male":"1250–Kuollut","1205–Male":"1205–Kuollut","1210–Female":"1210–Kuollut","1205":"1205","1225":"1225","1210":"1210","1320":"1320","1276":"1276","1230?":"1230","1230":"1230","1250":"1250","1260":"1260","1270":"1270","Abt 1229":"noin 1229","Stockham, Devon, England":"Brockham, Devon, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Somerset, England":"Somerset, England","Raleigh, Devon, England":"Farleigh, Devon, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta",",Devon,England":"Devon, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","England":"Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"1230?–":"1230–Décédée